Camera Calibration: Used to estimate the physical, optical and positional parameters of a camera lens and image sensor. This is just a process. We usually use tools like ArUco marker or AprilTag.

ArUco: It is a deterministic, rule based computer algorithm vision. Not trained using traditional methods. Square sign with wide black borders, and inner matrix. Preprocessing: The camera feed is converted to a grayscale image and then undergoes thresholding (binarization), turning the image into pure black and white. It detects the edges of the image, and due to tilt of the object, the image usually appears as a trapezium and not a square. It straightens out the shape and makes it a square instead. This is done using perceptive transformation, and the shift is noted down, which detects the tilt in an object. Acts as a spatial anchor for computer vision systems. Similar to a QR code, it allows a camera to instantly recognize an object's location, orientation, and distance in the real world.

AprilTag is similar to arUco tag.  But AprilTags utilize a line-gradient approach based on pixel intensity changes, making them highly resilient to poor lighting. ArUco markers rely on simpler edge detection (contour finding), which requires high contrast to work well

